Overload.descr:
Ensures that one or more statements are always executed after a Try statement finishes.
try {
    ...
} finally {
    ...
}

-- OR --

try {
    ...
} catch [ErrorClass] [as ErrorObj] {
    ...
} else {
    ...
} finally {
    ...
}

Always executed, even if Retry, Throw or any other 
control-flow statement is present in Try. 

Must come after Try statement.

Repeats one or more statements once for each key-value pair in an object.
for value in <expression> {
    ...
}

-- OR --

for index , value in <expression> {
    ...
}

Supports more than 2 variables for classes with __Enum(n) method.

KeyName: Single character from the keyboard or one of the key names from the key list, such as a mouse/controller button: B, 5, LWin, RControl, Alt, Enter, Escape, LButton, MButton, Joy1; explicit virtual key code: vkFF, VK41;
Mode: P = physical state T = toggle state (CapsLock, NumLock, ScrollLock)
Returns: 1 if the key is down (or toggled on) or 0 if it is up (or toggled off).

loop [Count] {
    Statements
}

variable inside loop: 
  A_Index (common to all loops)

Compares a value with multiple cases and executes the statements of the first match.
switch <expression> [, CaseSense] { case Value1: Statements... case Value2: Statements... default: Statements... }
CaseSense: 'On'|1 = The search is case-sensitive. The letters A-Z are considered identical to their lowercase a-z counterparts. 'Off'|0 = The search is case-insensitive.

Guards one or more statements against runtime errors and values thrown by the Throw statement.
try {
    ...
} catch [ErrorClass] [as ErrorObj] {
    ...
} else {
    ...
} finally {
    ...
}

-- OR --

try <statement>
try <expression>

-- OR --

try if  { ...
try for { ...

Applies a post-condition to the continuation of a Loop or For-loop.
loop [Count] {
    ...
} until (expression)

for i, value in Array {
    ...
} until (expression)

while (expression) {
    ...
} until (expression)

The expression is evaluated once after each iteration, 
and is evaluated even if Continue was used. 

If the expression evaluates to False, the loop continues; 
otherwise, the loop is broken 
and execution continues at the line following Until.

It is shorthand for the Break inside Loop body:

Loop {
    ...
    if (expression)
        break
}

Performs one or more statements repeatedly until the specified expression evaluates to False.
while (expression) {
    ...
}

-- OR --

while (expression) {
    ...
} until (expression)

The expression (pre-conddition) is evaluated once before each iteration. 

If the expression evaluates to True, the body of the loop is executed; 
otherwise, execution jumps to the line following the loop's body.

The loop may optionally be followed by an Else statement,
which is executed if the loop had zero iterations.

while (expression) {
    ...
} else {
    ...
}

To apply post-condition, use Until statement:
while true {
    ...
} until (expression)

Exits (terminates) any type of loop statement.
break [LoopLabel|Level]

outer:
Loop 3 {
    Loop 3 {
        if true
            break outer  ; Equivalent to break 2
    }
}

Specifies one or more statements to execute if a value or error is thrown during execution of a Try statement.
try ... catch [ErrorClass] [as var] { ... }
Error Classes: MemoryError = Memory allocation failed. OSError = Win32 func call failed. TargetError = Gui target could not be found (window or control). TimeoutError = SendMessage timed out. TypeError = Unexpected type (subjective, use as desired). UnsetError = Var does not exist, or is unset / no value. - MemberError - PropertyError - MethodError - UnsetItemError ValueError = Unexpected type (subjective, use as desired). IndexError = Requested __Index[] was invalid or out of range. ZeroDivisionError

Skips the rest of a loop body begins a new iteration (continues the loop).
continue [LoopLabel|Level]

outer:
Loop 3 {
    Loop 3 {
        if true
            continue outer  ; Equivalent to continue 2
    }
}
